They belong rather to the older generation, they can not get involved in work, for example, for health reasons, they are free and do not have children.
The one who "becomes" a witch is sent into isolation so as not to threaten the rest of the village.
"This fate can only be achieved very rarely."
“Even young healthy women don’t give up because they help with work and give birth to children,” says a nun who, in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, takes care of more than a hundred women who have been evicted from their communities.
The local government has now decided to take action against the unusual "social measure".
She published an information booklet to help limit the witch hunt.
It's got a hook.
"More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso are unable to read," Die Standard said in a statement.
