The offices also include a nursery, understood the architects
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect to hide a mini-school with everything that goes with it - with colorful walls, fancy furniture, a bunch of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, it can be visited by children of Arch.Design employees.
Arch.Design, a project-architectural company whose studios were the source of a number of important Brno buildings, had been counting on space for its corporate mini-school since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
It employs almost 90 people, mostly at the age of the baby boom, and it was important for the women designers and architects to be able to get back to work quickly.
Along with the possibility of shortened periods, the nursery is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees as part of a social program.
Thus, builders and architects have the opportunity to combine demanding work with childcare.
The mini-school was invented by Arch.Design employees themselves and with the support of the management they managed to obtain a grant from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s mini-school is funded by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to grant funding (grant of CZK 2.8 million), they were able to purchase equipment and provide qualified personnel and operations for two years.
After exhausting the financial grant (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to run the mini-school for 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of the project took one year and the application for the grant was significantly assisted by Economy Rating.
The care is provided by qualified staff, the children are cared for all day by a nurse and a school teacher, so children can go to kindergarten without age restrictions, despite the fact that most of them are older than 3 years.
Because it is a "mini-school", only 5 children can be present at the same time, but more will be replaced during the day.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of parents and children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten regardless of the hierarchy of positions in the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the program load in a mini-school is comparable to the framework program of pre-school education.
Children not only play here, but they are also provided with quality teaching - from basic knowledge to preparation for school benches, English is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, games, but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check on their child at any time and avoid stressful situations with delayed pick-up of children from kindergartens away from their parents’ workplace.
As a result, parents use their working hours more productively.
It is no wonder that this creates a naturally loyal relationship between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design has thus become one of the Czech companies that offer a significant benefit in recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and through this program has strengthened personnel marketing.
The house of bones fascinates even after 100 years. Look into the interiors of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>
The roof looks like the back of an ancient lizard, the staircase resembles a dinosaur’s spine, and the balconies are open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> house in Barcelona by Catalan architect Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Thanks to its organic shapes, the house has earned the nickname House of Bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft curves, all this is typical of the Art Nouveau art of Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
The front of the house unfolds dream lines, soft colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
When observing in detail, you can see the geometry, rhythm and precisely thought-out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house sounds even more dramatic, it is illuminated so that the impression of the brightness of colors is even stronger.
The twisting and twisting of shapes with the same degree also appears in the interiors.
Wood in the waves copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of the door, hooks and bars.
Batll<0xC3><0xB3> House, which stands in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Gr<0xC3><0xA1>cia No. 43, was built in 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took place over two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, rich industrialist Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, originally insisted on demolishing the old building and building a brand new one, but soon adopted Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> was not designed by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> himself.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was on his design board that decorations for the representative apartment of the property owner and the use of mosaics on the facade were created.
A number of other artists and artists also worked on the facade.
The joint work on the designs of Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> started Jujol’s successful cooperation with Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Jujol took part in the construction of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s Casa Mil<0xC3><0xA1> and the G<0xC3><0xBC>ell Park, where Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s other works are located.
From the local house soon after its completion, it earned the nickname "House of Bones" thanks to its organic shapes.
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening windows, began to call it a "calling house".
It is also said that on the top of the building is depicted the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> designed a unique central heating system with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
It may seem bizarre that they have a forty-five degree inclination.
In creating Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>, he absolutely did not respect the building regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be bound by them.
At the beginning of the construction, he received a building permit from the city, but the data he provided on the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, when it was completed, the city council was shocked by the result and asked for a correction.
For example, councillors resented the fact that the building interfered with the pillars and the public sidewalk.
The correction never happened, on the contrary: only fifteen days after the call of the city district, Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3> applied (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor was a lounge and on the third floor was a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented jewelry.
The entire six-storey house crosses the stairs, which can be climbed up to the roof terrace itself.
The essential elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon door, and a larger company can communicate comfortably together, without at the same time maintaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
In addition to the new fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, the house with Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s reconstruction also received an unusual roof and two additional floors.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s play with light, blue and white glazed tiles, which are lined with the inner courtyard, and skylights, is also impressive.
The game of two colors adds maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which absorbs the sun's rays on the contrary.
The Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, which was listed in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by anyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and the most generous apartment available to the public.
The owners decided to take this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the one hundred and fiftyth anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They stayed at the tours, as they found that it was a very advantageous business and in addition, the tours were extended by common and attic areas, including the roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is definitely not negligible, it is 16.50 euros and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards have a 20% discount.
The suma greatly exceeds the price of entry to other Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> buildings in the city.
