Attorneys for the Justice Department have cleared Senator John Ensign of a criminal charge related to his affair with a former campaign adviser and his efforts to secure the lobby, lawyers told the senator on Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat that Mr. Ensign, a Nevada Republican, faced and who was, until the scandal, considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012. His affair got into national headlines and damaged his career.
Mr Ensign’s office said he was “certainly pleased” with the decision, which followed almost a year of investigations.
The senator could still face disciplinary proceedings at the Senate Ethics Committee.
Ensign's lawyers said the Justice Department "has informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer the subject of the investigation and that there are no plans to bring further charges against him in this matter."
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The decision came as a surprise to many ethical lawyers outside the Justice Department who argued that there was serious evidence that Mr. Ensign was preparing to violate the federal lobbying ban.
Interviews, e-mails, and other documents published in October 2009 in the New York Times stated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, one of his assistants, secure a lucrative lobby to silence Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's relationship with him.
Mrs. Hampton used to work as a treasurer in the Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political supporters to find a job for Mr. Hampton and to support their views after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, so much do the documents and interviews state.
Since Hampton had been Mr. Ensign's assistant until recently, he was barred from lobbying his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethics experts say that the unusual settlement of Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were friends before the affair, appeared to contradict the prohibition of lobbying.
The evidence that was published "appears to be a clear case of preparation for a violation of the law," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients who are being investigated by the government.
While Justice Department officials refused to explain the reasons for the decision in Senator Ensign’s case, Mr. Brand and other lawyers specializing in ethics said the department was cautious about political charges after a large number of failures, including last year’s decision to suspend the defendant’s lawsuit against him.
Federal prosecutors “clearly concealed the weapons,” said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a advocacy group that filed several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"It basically indicates that the laws don't apply to high-ranking government officials," she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign’s chief lawyer, said in an interview that he was called by the DOJ’s attorney general on Monday and then the next day, and told him that the DOJ had found no charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's defense team is working with the plaintiffs to convince them that the senator, as his office repeated in Wednesday's statement, "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr Coggins refused to specify the legal arguments he had submitted to the State Prosecutors.
"I'm not happy to compare the details of my discussions with the Justice Department except that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to stop investigating a separate complaint in which the ethics group alleges that the payment of Ensign's parents to the Hamptons of $96,000 violated federal election law.
The Election Commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money meant nothing but a gift.
One company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find a lobbying job was NV Energy, a major Nevada corporation that had long supported the senator.
One email from December 2008 showed that after Mr. Hampton started working as a lobbyist in the company, the head of Mr. Ensign's staff - John Lopez - communicated with Mr. Hampton and told him that he had "kicked" the Ministry of the Interior on the subject under discussion.
Mr. Ensign also attended lunch with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and invited the Secretary of Transportation to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after they hired Mr. Hampton for lobbying work.
When news of the affair first surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After months of stagnation, Mr. Ensign told reporters two weeks ago that he planned to run for a third term in the Senate.
In a report that Mr. Ensign is no longer the target of an investigation into the crime, his spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the Justice Department and end the entire investigation.
