Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit commission was also civilised, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that close co-operation has built mutual respect for several months that transcends the ideological divide that still divides members.
And it is quite difficult to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a testing period - probing each other's signs of collegiality and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and electoral patience towards renewed party war.
Therefore, Tuesday's hearing and its subsequent evaluation of participants was also conducted with minimal demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too wide and too deep to propose a rapid change in the conditions that have prevailed here for the past two years.
