Zapatero and the Red German Line
Berlin decided to maintain the euro, but set the conditions for the whole Union.
Tensions in the markets provoked a double government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Zapatero proposed a new adaptation measure, from reducing taxes for small and medium-sized enterprises, through the regulation of private intermediary agencies or the cancellation of 426 euros for the unemployed without benefits, until after the privatization of 49% of AENA (Spanish airports and air traffic management - note.
On the other hand, Vice-President Elena Salgadov<0xC3><0xA1>, with the support of former Prime Minister Felipe Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez, joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility to start the current crisis.
How to interpret this movement?
Let it be said in advance that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, this is another point in the complex process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future will be, which runs counter to the idea of adhering to the old traditions held by a large part of the other members.
Faced with European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first of these is a strong eurozone, which would include Germany, but also Austria or the Netherlands, while the southern states would leave the currency zone.
The second is a return to March – although now it may seem like a scifi, this version has broad public support, approaching 50% of the population.
The third option, according to the German proposals, is to rework the euro with greater macroeconomic supervision, budgetary rigour, fines for the guilty states, possible delays in payments for some of them, and with the extension of possible costs of regulation to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time now, so there is no room for slurs now.
First, when in 2009 the International Monetary Fund and the European Commission instigated deficits, the German government pulled out a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016 onwards.
This was the first sign of a contradiction between what Germany considered to be right (plans of fiscal rigour and stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, practiced.
The latter was shown by this Central European country, when Merkel was painfully delaying the decision to rescue Greece.
It has already been the subject of sharp criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and the public opinion that was also published were strongly against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again appeared with a clear position when she demanded to reform the European Union's conventions so as to allow the rescue of a Member State while at the same time giving private creditors the obligation to bear part of the costs.
This opinion was interpreted as anti-European, as it accelerated the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, although somewhat tempered, has been approved, and in the coming months we should be following the Union's reform process, which should allow for these measures from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And it tells us all that, although there is now a need to take measures with which it seems to disagree too much, the old functioning of the euro will end from this date.
The year 2013 will see the birth of a new currency zone, in which violators of the rules will be severely sanctioned and may be forced to declare a deferral of payments, and the private sector will also have to bear some of the costs.
Germany suggests to us that we must take a strict path of growth with an increase in the rate of savings and investment, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital reserves.
Another option based on receivables and construction, with huge gaps in the balance of payments that prevailed in the years of Spain’s booming growth, they simply do not intend to tolerate.
The offer is clear.
And we'd make a mistake if we didn't understand.
It’s not just about restoring the public deficit to 3% in 2013.
What they want from us is much harder.
And the worst part is, under these conditions, we could be wrong.
I hope that these current turbulences will replace more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities they give us until spring 2013.
It seems that Prime Minister Zapatero also understood this and his double statement (reforms promised after last Saturday’s meeting with big companies and yesterday’s announcement of new measures) suggests that despite criticism of Merkel, the path has opened up to the idea that things need to be put right.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and it doesn’t seem to want to move with it.
And from the possibilities that can be considered, leaving the eurozone full of not-so-serious countries cannot be ruled out.
Well, Germany will always be able to tell us that it warned us.
Sport and breaking the rules
Finty, as shown by Alonso and Ramos in the match against Ajax, show the wit not the intention to escape punishment.
The alleged exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramose) in the Champions League match against Ajax on 23 November caused a sea of ink to be written on whether or not this is unsportsmanlike behavior, and whether UEFA should possibly bribe both players.
As is known, a few minutes before the end of the game (which their team had clearly won) the named players one by one deliberately lost time at the moment when the foul was to be played to provoke the referee, and he showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, both players will meet the prescribed penalty in the next match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid finishing in their group at the head - and will be able, stripped of the cards, to proceed to the next stage.
In the end, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee awarded coach José Mourinho a two-game penalty and the guilty players received a fine.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, i.e. rules that are unwritten, but follow each other.
Part of the discussion in this case was due to the fact that its participant was the Real Madrid team (which in its anthem boasts nobility and honor, and which has already punished its players for similar acts), and also, it seems, due to the dramatization led by Mourinho, which adds to its long history of comedy.
In any case, the debate is about whether this type of action, which is not explicitly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether these facts circumvent the law; in fact, it is an action respecting sports rules, the meaning of which, of course, seems to be trying.
It is decided what type of damage such actions cause to the sports spirit.
One of the requirements of sports behavior is the physical inviolability of opponents, which was not violated in these cases, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these things that characterize a clean game is to avoid allowing players to have an advantage over an opponent's team due to their offense - which is also not the case here.
So the paradox of the action of Real Madrid players is that what we normally characterize as a gesture or circumvention of the law did not happen, there was no hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid sanctions, but this behavior should be as obvious as possible in order to receive punishment.
They waited and liked to be punished.
The next question, however, is what advantage will the perpetrators of their intentional offense have.
It should be noted here that the opponent does not get into a disadvantageous position and that there is no benefit in the current match, because the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next game, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage obviously lies in the fact that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards, which could jeopardize their participation in the future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, so at first glance the team can be eliminated, and in addition, with this action, the players will be penalized, and they will go to the second round of cards, in which it is enough to exclude one card less than in the first round.
So as the rounds continue, it will not be entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the spirit of sport, which includes making strategic decisions that will allow you to get the maximum benefit within the rules.
in the case we are dealing with here, the players did not aim to avoid punishment (which would be a clear case of circumvention of the rules), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made strategic decisions without avoiding punishment or running away from it.
Although the line between making a joke and breaking the rules is not quite clear, I believe that in this case it was definitely a joke.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because it was two self-exclusions and because of the way in which the instructions to provoke them from the leadership were transmitted.
The violation of sports principles by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
