U.S. changes visa rules
People will have to contact the Visa Service Centres before they can be interviewed at the Consular Section; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa process at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to contact the Visa Service Centres (abbreviated as ASC) before an interview at the Consular Section.
The staff of the ASC will collect the biometric information of the applicant and these will be evaluated by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, there will be no need to pay the fee for arranging the meeting, the second for processing the application and another for delivering the document by transport service.
The applicant will pay only one fee, which will cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for a visa for traders and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular officer, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and fingerprints will be taken from them.
Given that biometric information will be collected at the ASC, applicants who will require a second interview at the Consular Department will spend a shorter time there than in the past.
Likewise, those who apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra fee for the service of $26.
For more information on the new procedure for applying for a visa, visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
