Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of emissions from a car park across the planet.
In Copenhagen last year, a large country with a significant share of emissions such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, engaged in voluntary plans to reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance to achieve a stabilisation of climate warming at 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 so that it can be ruled out that it will not get out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, is the product of light.
With fluo-compact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new DEL bulbs, we will reduce this consumption by two more times.
Fluo-compact bulbs last on average from 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new DEL bulbs, which he put into production this week by Philips - this company allegedly participated in a UN study - have an estimated lifespan of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than the incandescent bulb, giving us an idea of the potential savings with a replacement plan that would be 100 times more expensive.
