Climate: How France Hacked Its Financing Promises
A year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to test the implementation of fast-start or early-start financing promises made by developed countries.
And the great French hacks were revealed
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion in 2010-2012.
The European Union has pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion over three years and France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (that is 420 million annually).
At the launch of COP16, the EU pulled out a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: a report detailing the actions of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
Transparent operations are invaluable and valued at their true value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do the same and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to deliver on its pledge of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on the detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, these funds are "new and additional" to ensure that the increased burden is implemented without prejudice to public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 to be a reference year: international funding has been maintained and it is adding another 150 million over three years to the title of financing fast start.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment deadlines or with deadlines at the level of public development aid.
On the other hand, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" of 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of public aid for the development of d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, the total amount of aid granted by France to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even decrease) in order to comply with its commitment regarding the financing of "new and additional"...
Another crucial element is the distribution of gifts and loans.
There is no rule there yet and everyone chooses their own way of calculating.
Some, such as France, consider that 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> borrowed is equal to 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be proven for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to reducing emissions, consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we get as the equivalent of one euro that we give... , but we should not take it as an egalitarian for the sake of its value.
But France can provide only such a justification: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros, of which it makes up 91.5% of the loan (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of the donations (36,1 million euros) - see the EU document to verify it yourself.
It is the only country in the EU that uses the loan on this scale.
Germany has requested 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) have complied with their obligations with 100% of the donations.
In other words, when the absolute majority of the European Union gives <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 on as part of fulfilling its promise, it gives France only 10 cents and considers this effort comparable.
What a beautiful piece of cake!
To sum up, in its financing "fast start" France operates with a double check: on the one hand with the development of stocks over time and on the other with a real financial burden.
Despite spending only 36.1 million euros, he can convince himself that he is spending 420 million euros "new and additional" in connection with his promises.
The manipulation of the finance minister (because it seems that although it is Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why would Member States continue to donate when it is enough to borrow?) and when negotiating, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The chapter on early funding is just a small, relatively short-term question in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could also be a grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope this isn't our case.
Whatever it is, it is necessary to draw on the knowledge of this first year of early funding.
First, France should announce a change in its way of keeping the accounts for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respect for its obligations and decency and fairness towards the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussing deposits for long-term financing (another key chapter currently under discussion): let us not avoid the question of "additionality" or the way in which loans are credited.
France should change its stance to become as progressive with these deposits as it is with others.
So everyone is putting their hope in the new environment minister, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who is coming to Cancun next week.
The surprising announcement of France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans could trigger an increase in the level of international confidence necessary to be able to move forward in the discussions.
Pesticide alarms that children are exposed to.
A 10-year-old child will one day be exposed to 81 different chemicals, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Future Generations Association (formerly the Rights and Conservation of Future Generations Movement).
The association, which notes that its results "do not have a significant statistical value in view of the low number of analyzed samples, but are characteristic of the processed issue", bought between July and September food commonly consumed in four meals and one light dish in a light dish.
These typical foods, including official recommendations - five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day - as well as sweets, were analyzed by research laboratories on chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate balance is crushing: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified among carcinogenic, possible or probable, and five substances are among the clear carcinogenic substances, as well as 37 substances that could act as disruptors to inner-extrusion (PE) glands, according to studies by several research institutes.
"Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, in our research we see well that the reality in consumer exposure to contaminants, possibly carcinogenic, and/or PE is contagion," the association said.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk contain in themselves about ten residues with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven as certain carcinogens, as is the case with about twenty residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, cited by the study as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same goes for the green beans from Kenya, included in the lunch, where studies have found traces of strong insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, minced beef steak, canned tuna, and even goose and chewing gum were spiked with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
Salmon steak for dinner was the "richest" with 34 discovered chemical residues, and even an analysis of a plastic plate used to heat food in a microwave oven did not avoid analysis.
The final risk to consumers of this “coke of contaminants” is likely to be underestimated,” the study concludes.
The Environmental Europe-Greens Association (EE-LV) has proposed "face to face an urgent situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop "the growth of civilizational diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) examined the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
